Real signal for respiration

The sample frequency of the signal is 200 Hz.
fs = 200;
x = csvread('Respiration_Fs200Hz.csv');
NSamples = length(x);
% Create time vector respective to samples vector
n = 0:(NSamples-1);
t = n/fs; % We can think other forms to create time vector
Plot the time signal
fig = figure('Position',[300 100 500 300],'color','w');
plot(t,x)
xlabel('time (s)')
ylabel('Amp')
title('Respiration signal')
Here we compute the fft of the signal and plot results (Magnitude and spectrum) fror results
Y = fft(x);
Y1 = fftshift(Y);
Nfft = length(Y);
w = linspace(0,1,Nfft);
w1 = linspace(-0.5,0.5,Nfft);
fig = figure('Position',[100 100 900 500],'color','w');
% Spectrum as returned by FFT function
ax1 = subplot(2,2,1);
plot(w,abs(Y))
title('|X[k]|: Magnitude')
ax2 = subplot(2,2,3);
plot(w,angle(Y))
title('\angle X[k]: Phase')
xlabel('normalized frequency')
% Spectrum as returned by FFT function
ax1 = subplot(2,2,2);
plot(w1,abs(Y1))
title('|X[k]|: Magnitude')
ax2 = subplot(2,2,4);
plot(w1,angle(Y1))
title('\angle X[k]: Phase')
xlabel('normalized frequency')
We create frequency vector and plot one side spectrum
To get the one seide sectrum
P2 = abs(Y/Nfft);
P1 = P2(1:Nfft/2+1);
P1(2:end-1) = 2*P1(2:end-1);
% Values represented in dB
P = 20*log10(P1);
% create frequency vector
% know that the high frequency contained in sampled signal is fs/2
% fs/2 ->(eqivalent pi/2)
f = linspace(0,fs/2,Nfft/2+1);
fig = figure('Position',[100 100 500 500],'color','w');
ax1 = subplot(2,1,1);
plot(f,P1)
ax1 = subplot(2,1,2); hold on
plot(f,20*log10(P1))
ylim([-100 0])
[Val,Loc] = max(P);
plot(f(Loc),P(Loc),'Marker','v','MarkerFaceColor','r')
str = sprintf('%.2f Hz',f(Loc));
text(f(Loc),P(Loc),str)
box on
xlabel('frequency (Hz)')

Recover the signal

YRecov = Y1;
Mag = abs(YRecov);
Phase = angle(YRecov);
Mag(1) = 0;
% Phase(1) = 0;
Mag(Mag<25) = 0;
% Phase(Mag<24) = 0;
YRecov = Mag.*exp(1i*Phase);
xRecov = real(ifft(YRecov));
fig = figure('Position',[300 100 500 300],'color','w');
hold on
plot(t,x)
plot(t,xRecov)
ylim([-1.5 1.5])
box on

STFT and specrogram fundamentals

In the second part of the class we will initiate brifly the fundamentals of STFT. We use this concept to obtain the spectrogram of recorded audio signal
% Read audio Signal
FileName = 'PaiTe.wav';
[x,fs] = audioread(FileName);
NSamples = length(x);
t = (0:NSamples-1)/fs;
% Plot time signal & spectrogram of original signal
fig = figure('Position',[100 100 900 600],'color','w');
% Plot time signal
ax1 = subplot(3,1,1);
plot(t,x);
tl = title('a) Time signal','Interpreter','latex');
set(ax1,'TickLabelInterpreter','latex','FontSize',13);
% Plot spectrogram
% pkg load signal; % We need to uncommnet this in octave
nfft = 1024; % number fft points for spectrogram (STFT)
WLength = round(.05*fs); % Number of samples for each window segment used in STFT
PercentOverlap = 0.8; % 80 percent overlap
ax2 = subplot(3,1,[2 3]);
[Pxx,tPxx,f] = My_STFT(x,fs,WLength,PercentOverlap);
Pxx_dB = 10*log10(Pxx);
surf(tPxx,f/1e3,Pxx_dB,'edgecolor','none');
axis tight, view(0,90)
tl = title('b) Signal spectrogram','Interpreter','latex');
xlabel('t(s)','Interpreter','latex');
ylabel('f(kHz)','Interpreter','latex');
set(ax2,'TickLabelInterpreter','latex','FontSize',13);

Show the STFT code

function [Pxx,tPxx,f] = My_STFT(x,fs,windowLen,PercentOverlap)
NSamples = length(x);
%windowLen; % Window length in samples
overlap = round(PercentOverlap*windowLen); % overlap between segments in samples
nfft = 1024; % number of points in frequency for DFT
Step = windowLen - overlap;
EndSamples = windowLen:Step:NSamples;
StartSamples = EndSamples - windowLen +1;
f = linspace(0,fs/2,nfft/2+1);
tPxx = 0.5*(StartSamples + EndSamples)/fs;
NSteps = length(tPxx);
% STFT implementation
Pxx = zeros(nfft/2+1,NSteps);
Window = hamming(windowLen);
for iStep = 1:NSteps
xWindow = x(StartSamples(iStep):EndSamples(iStep)).*Window;
X = fft(xWindow,nfft);
% Hold the first half part of the spectrum
P2 = abs(X/(nfft));
P1(2:nfft/2+1) = P2(2:nfft/2+1);
P1(1) = P2(1);
Pxx(:,iStep) = P1;
end
end
